snippet.textDisplay: generally, the kind of people who get push notifications for major news outlets (the times, cnn, washpo) are subscribers to these organizations that regularly read their content. the purpose of push notifications for news organizations isnt to warn people of threats -- local authorities are generally responsible for that -- but to deliver provacative, interesting stories to the user. essentially, to prompt them to read the news (which, is actually really important in this day in age. we need the reminder to stay informed). i think the giant bird example is actually a great example of a well done push notification. science journalism is declining, despite how absolutely paramount it is in an informed society. fun, interesting stories like that entice readers to learn something, and then they may be more inclined to read science stories in the future -- which isn't a bad thing. reading science makes people more deferent to scientific authority and then we dont have shit like climate change and measles outbreaks to deal with. i know that's off base from the point of the joke but im frankly disappointed in this episode because it not only makes fun of extremely respectable media outreach efforts (if more people supported a free press these outlets wouldnt even need to bother people with constant notifications and reminders to support their journalism) but the angle you took was terrible and this show's honestly just stupid and poorly written. i honestly love last week tonight and i think the show does genuinely good things to reach younger demographics and educate people on less-reported issues but im disappointed by this. didnt mean to go off like this but thats how it be sometimes i guess. thanks
